  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Background:

      Hemorrhoids of grade 3 and 4 can be treated either by conventional, rather invasive
      procedures, like Milligan-Morgan or Ferguson or by modern, less invasive procedures with less
      postoperative pain. Doppler guided hemorrhoidal artery ligation and stapled hemorrhoidopexy
      are examples for such modern procedures. Hemorrhoidal artery ligation causes less post
      operative pain than stapled hemorrhoidopexy, however the former has a higher recurrence rate.
      Combining hemorrhoidal artery ligation with rectoanal repair should reduce the recurrence
      rate without increasing the post operative pain.

      Hypothesis and aim:

      The study tries to prove the assumption that combined hemorrhoidal artery ligation and
      rectoanal repair cause less pain and have less post operative complications than stapled
      hemorrhoidopexy.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
